source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3653
Reason: The compound in question can be dissected into several structural components that influence its melting point: the basic unit of the molecule comprises aromatic rings and heterocyclic components, which provide a substantial basis for the melting point. Starting with the core components: (1) Benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C, but the introduction of heteroatoms and the formation of heterocyclic rings generally increase this melting point due to additional ring strain and possible hydrogen bonding; for the dihydrotriazolothiadiazole moiety, this is estimated to add approximately +100°C. (2) The presence of ethoxy (–OCH2CH3) and methoxy (–OCH3) groups on the aromatic rings introduces additional van der Waals forces and possible hydrogen bonding interactions; the methoxy group may increase the melting point by +20°C, while the ethoxy group, being larger, may add +30°C. (3) The connection between the triazolothiadiazole core and the aromatic rings adds structural rigidity, which could further raise the melting point, estimated conservatively at +10°C for the framework. (4) Each aromatic ring can contribute to an increase in the melting point due to the potential for π-π interactions and increased molecular stiffness; assigning +20°C per aromatic ring results in +40°C for two rings. The cumulative effect of these contributions can be used to predict the overall melting point.
